column168: Shortly before 8pm, employees of the Union Pacific RR spotted two cars (ACFX 86869 and ACFX 79300) with an unknown substance running down the side. It appeared to be coming from the dome area of each car. Upon further inspection, it was identified as diesel. The UP Hazmat Team were deployed, as were Viva Environmental, to neutralize the situation. Western representatives arrived at the scene at 9pm. Upon inspection of the cars, it was readily obvious that the dome bolts were not properly secured prior to release. The Hazmat Team found 6 loose bolts on ACFX 79300 and 5 loose bolts on ACFX 86869 (they were a little more than "hand tight"). The gaskets were found to be worn, but not to the point where they would not properly seal had the bolts been properly tightened. The gaskets were replaced as a precaution, the bolts were secured, and the cars were released at approx 10pm.  No diesel spillage reached the ground. The estimated amount on the side of the car was less than a gallon. Viva Environmental cleaned the effected areas.
column169: Re-emphasize the importance of following guidelines for properly securing tankcars for transportation. Appropriate disciplinary action for the individual loader.

column168: On December 4, 2007, at approximately 0150 hours, a railway tankcar UTLX 48182, loaded with Residue, Diisopropyl Ether, flammable, UN1159 PG II, was reported leaking at the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) Baton Rouge yard. The tank car was discovered venting from a loose vapor valve and and loose secondary closure plug. The release amount was estimated as vapor from the liquid commodity residue off gassing due to pressure differential caused by the afternoon sun. The shipper representative responded to the site closing the valve and tightening the plug.  There were no injuries, no damage to the environment.     CODE: 136  NARRI: 5(4+3+0)x(2+0
column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: The package was found leaking, upon opening the box we found a plastic bottle inside a plastic bag. The bottle had tape around the screw on cap, but the material had eaten away at the adhesive on the tape. The bottle, surrounded by styrofoam peanuts, was laying in the box on it's side. Hence, the arrows were going a direction contrary to the inner bottle. In addition, some of the peanuts had melted as a result of the spill. I spoke to the shipper. Shipper said that they bought their UN tested packaging from Uline Inc, Waukegan, IL. I called Uline who said that Tyger Scientific was not a cutomer, at least not in Ewing, NJ. The shipper had been trained in 2005 by DG Suppliers Inc. The FAA was notified, I spoke to SA at 1830 hrs CST on 12/1/2007. The freight is being held pending an FAA inspection.

column168: During unloading operations Dichloroacetyl Chloride reacted with water in the unloading line generating pressure and causing a gasket in the unloading line to rupture.  Vapor from the reaction (Hydrogen Chloride and water vapor) was released into the air.  Site emergency responders shut down the unloading process, and initiated a deluge water spray of the area to knock down vapors.  After the deluge spray, air monitoring was conducted in the unloading area and down wind both inside the facility boundry, and outside the facility boundary.  No vapors were detected beyond the immmediate release area.
column169: Unloading procedures have been modified to "purge" the unloading lines with Nitrogen prior to connecting the CTMV.  This will eliminate any water within the lines.  The ruptured gasket has been replaced.

column168: On 12/01/07 at 0918 personnel in CSXT Etowah, TN rail yard discovered PROX 16338, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, leaking from the fill hole.  The area was isolated and the shipper, Chemtrade Logistics, was notified of the incident.  Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor was dispatched to the scene and found two of the three fill hole bolts were less than tool tight.  Hepaco personnel tightened the bolts and decontaminated the rail car.  The leak was secured and the car released for transport.      NARRI: 5 (5+5+0)*(2+0) = 100  Cause Code: 224

column168: On December 4th 2007, the conductor on the A73904 reported a strong odor from tank car UTLX 646249; a residue last contained Corrosive Liquid NOS (Sodium Sulfide Solutions).  He also reported a white residue on the B-end right side on the trucks and wheels.  This car was set out of his train into the transfer track at Bainbridge, GA.  State notification and notification to Chemtrec was made.  SWS, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the manway gasket was compressed with a significant amount of rust and corrosion on it.  The manway nozzle and cover were also covered with rust and corrosion.  The nozzle and manway cover were cleaned, a new gasket was installed and properly secured.  The car was decontaminated before movement.        NARRI: 5(4+5+0)*(2+0) = 90  Cause Code = 209

column168: On Monday, December 10th at 0354 hours personnel in the CSXT Cayce Yard discovered CITX35618, a loaded tank car of Anhydrous Ammonia releasing vapors from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and Chemtrec (report number 2007-12-10-00022) assisted in notifying the shipper, Koch Nitrogen.  Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that vapors were being emitted from the "B" end liquid line plug valve stem.  The response contractor was unable to secure the release of product.  The valve was "capped" and an application for FRA Movement Approval was submitted.  Upon obtaining FRA Movement Approval (FRA-07120362) the railcar was forwarded to destination in a dedicated train without incident.  The car owner, Tanner Industries was informed that they must apply for a new approval prior to moving the tank car for repairs.  Approximately two pounds of product was released into atmosphere.  Cause Code:297  NARRI:  2 (5+9+0) X (2+0) = 56
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 12/11/2007 at 1152 hrs personnel in the CSXT Queensgate Yard  discovered GATX 72994, a loaded tank car of UN 1789, Hydrochloric Acid Solution, had the rupture disk inspection cap off (still attached to the leash). The rupture disk was found blown. Less than one gallon of product was on top of car and manway area.  The car was isolated and Veolia Environmental Services responded.  The shipper and Chemtrec were notified.  Contractor decontaminated the residue on the top of the car and replaced the blown rupture disk.  At no time was product found to have left the car and fall to the ground. The car was secured and then was released for transportation. This incident did require a special switching move to allow safe access to the car to allow for Dow personnel to perform functions.  Cause Code:  441  NARRI:  5 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100

column168: In removing the tote from the trailer the fork truck was at the point of leveling into the trailer at the same time that the forks were entering the cage surrounding the plastic gaylord. As everything shifted the metal guard that protects the valve at the bottom of the tote collapsed into the plastic neck of the valve. The fitting cracked at the junction with the tote. Liquid began to leak out and the fork lift operator continued to lift the tote out of the trailer and back out of the tail of the trailer onto the dock. He then enlisted help and they turned the tole over so that the broken valve was on its side above the level of the liquid. At this point I believe that with the tote on its side near the dock door there was an un noticed slow leak from a small hole near the top of the tote that allowed the majority of the liquid to leak onto the ground outside the dock door. Once this was noticed the tote was turned again to stop that leakage. The tote leaked approximately 190-gallons of the original 200-gallons. A hazmat contractor was hired to clean up the spill which included removal of contaminated gravel and soil next to the dock and under the trailer. The contaminated material will be disposed of properly.
column169: First order of business is corrective action to all employees involved concerning this incident not being reported immediately when it occurred. This is not acceptable and could easily become a more serious accident if the chemical involved were a more toxic item. I need to re-educate all employees   at 198 in the mandatory procedures in place for this type of incident. Secondly is a review with all involved in noting the integrity of the containers we pickup from this shipper. The next order of business is to review our handling procedures to prevent this type of fork lift damage in the future.

On December 5, 2007 at approximately 12:10 PM, we had an on-site release of approximately 22 gallons NPA.  Our employee inadvertently left one external valve open on the trailer he was intending to load the product into.  When he started to pump the product, he knew that he had forgotten to close the left side valve and within seconds he had shut down the engine cutting off the flow of product.  Consequently, 22 gallons of NPA was pumped onto the asphalt.  The product began to run down the alley way toward the NW corner of our site.  The driver ran to the NW corner, arriving before the product and immediately placed absorbent material and booms to contain the product and dike the sump.  While he was able to prevent most of the product from entering the sump and separator, it is estimated that about 10 gallons got past the absorbent materials into the oil/water separator.  Other employees joined the driver to put additional absorbent materials around the sump and oil/water separator to prevent further leakage.  They then cleaned up the NPA that had been collected within the various absorbent materials and put them into the appropriate containers for disposal. When the oil/water separator was opened, it was noted that the water level was below the outfall pipe.  Therefore, none of the product actually left the site.  The product/water mix within the separator was pumped out by approximately 3:45 PM into three tote bins.  An outside contractor then came in; pressure washed and cleaned the oil/water separator.  Samples from the totes were obtained for analysis to help determine proper disposal.  The outside contractor was on-site from approximately 4:00 PM to 5:15 PM.  This work was completed on 12/5/07.  More samples were taken of each tote on 12/21/07.  When we receive the analysis of the material we will profile the material for proper off-site disposal.
column169: We have instituted the following measures to help prevent any reoccurrence of this incident:  1.  Reviewed our standard operating procedures.    2.  Loading and unloading procedures were reviewed with the driver.  3.  Discussed the incident in the Dec. safety committee.  4.  Remind employees to think first and double check their work.  5.  Lids on the spill containment drums have been loosened so that only a quarter turn is necessary to remove the screw tops for quicker access to spill containment materials.  We intend to install a shut off valve to prevent future potential off-site releases if the configuration and size of the oil/water separator will allow it.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was intransit between the point of origin and the intended truck to truck facility.  Upon arrival at the intended truck to truck facility, it was discovered that a container on the vehicle had leaked allowing approximately 10 gallons of material to be released onto the floor of the van trailer.  Facility personnel immediately donned appropriate protective equipment and initiated appropriate response procedures.  Upon identification of the damaged container, it was determined that a 55 gallon steel drum had developed a pinhole leak.  During transportation, the  load movement allowed the liquid to escape.  The response crew collected all spill material using a suitable absorbent material and disposed of it into a 55 gallon drum.  The leaking drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon salvage drum.  The shipment was then transferred into a vehicle to continue on to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: At the time the vehicle was loaded, a closer inspection of the drums will be made by the driver.  The shipper was also cautioned regarding the shipment of older drums.  Use of overpack/salvage drums was recommended in the case of any questionable containers.

The box was found to be damp and emitting a petroleum-based odor. The box was segregated from the sort & opened. The box revealed what we believe to be a fuel control unit, leaking Jet A. The box was placed in a salvage drum. The FAA was notified, I spoke to FAA SA Theresa Spicer on 12/8/2007 at 10:15 hrs CST. There were no markings, labeling, shipping papers, emergency response information, no other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. The freight was held pending an FAA Inspection.

This was a DeWar that was supposed to be a dry dewar but there was some residueliquid still remaining in the container which caused gas and a small amount of liquid to leak out when the package was turned on its side. The amounts for the capacity and amount shipped above were estimated. The FAA in SFO (William Clark) was contacted and will investigate. The package is currently being held at the OAKH location.
column172: Box, wood or fiberboard not specified

column168: The box arrived at the Las Vegas FedEx station for sorting. The shipper is known to offer shipments of Dry Ice. That, coupled with the outer box was cold to the touch.The box was opened to reveal approximately 5 kg of Dry Ice. The outer box originally had a Class 9 label on it, but was mostly obscurred by brown packing tape. The FAA was notified, I spoke to SA Theresa Spicer. Due to the fragile nature of Dry Ice & that it would in all likely hood sublimate prior to an FAA inspection,I had local FedEx personnel take pictures of all six sides of the box & it's contents. Those pictures have been forwarded to & received by SA Spicer. There were no markings, labeling, shipping papers, emergency response information nor other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. The freight was released to the shipper.

The bottom of the box fell apart after being soaked in rainwater. The contents ofthe package included Dry Ice. Since the shipment originated from a medical facility and we feared the Dry Ice would sublimate prior to an FAA inspection, I directed FedEx personnel to take pictures of the six sides of the box & it's contents. There were two boxes that we found with undeclared Dry Ice from this shipper. The 2nd tracking number is: 7997-6785-6315. There were no markings, labeling, shiping papers, emergency response information or other indictor to communicate that the contents were regulated. The FAA was notified, I spoke to FAA SA David Schauffler. Because of the sensitive nature of the medical shipment, I authorized Fed Ex personnel to truck the Dry Ice packages back to the shipper. Pictures of the shipments will be emailed to SA Schauffler.

THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX GOT WET FROM RAINWATER, DESTROYING THE ADHESIVE PROPERTIES OF THE TAPE THAT HELD THE BOX FLAPS TOGETHER. THE CONTENTS ROLLED OUT OF THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX. THE DRUM INSIDE THE BOX HAD A CLASS 3 LABEL, PROPER SHIPPING NAME & UN# MARKINGS. SUBSEQUENTLY I CALLED THE SHIPPER, SPEAKING TO VICTOR NIX. MR. NIX ADVISED THIS WAS A SHIPMENT BEING RETURNED TO THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER & THAT IT HAD BEEN TRANSPORTED TO THE SIMMONS CO AS A REGULATED CLASS 3 MATERIAL. I NOTIFED THE FAA, I SPOKE TO FAA MANAGER CLIFF WEISS. SA VERONICA LAUGHLIN HAS INSPECTED THE SHIPMENT. THE FREIGHT HIS BEING HELD PENDING A DISOPOSITION. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING SHIPPING PAPERS, EMERGENCY RESPONSE INFORMATION NOR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS REGULATED.

After the cargo tank was loaded at shipper, the driver stopped at our facility which was 27 miles away.  When he returned to the trailer, he noticed a drip coming from the cargo tank near the front.  He drained his Heat in Transit line thinking maybe that was leaking but the drip continued.  There seemed to be product in the insulation.  Not sure of the cause, so the product was transferred to a different cargo tank and the delivery was completed.
column169: Once clean, the barrel was inspected and no visible cracks or pits were noticed.  24 psi was applied and it held pressure for over an hour. column168: Driver was enroute to home terminal after delivering lading to consignee. Trailer was empty with residue as driver approached port-of-entry in Arizona. Upon inspection Arizona Department of Transportation personnel noticed a small leak of acid at discharge closure. Vehicle was placed out-of-service until Company personnel arrived on scene to correct condition. It was determined that an incorrect gasket was used in the closure, which did not provide an adequate seal. Cargo tank was decontaminated and vehicle released.

column168: Customer provided a pre-built skid containing multiple boxes shrink-wrapped onto the skid.  Consolidation was declared "NON HAZARDOUS".  Load was picked up in Houston and moved by truck to Dallas for air shipment to destination.  During handling at the Dallas cargo facility, the consolidated load broke apart.  Found within the load was a single fibreboard box marked "Seat-belt Pre-tensioners" and "UN3268".  A class 9 hazard label was also displayed on the box.    Material was immediately secured as a "Class 1" material in accordance with the UPS Hazmat Security Plan.  All other packages were inspected for signs of hazmats.  None were found.    Customer was contacted, and they engaged a local hazmat vendor (L&L Pro Pac, Grapevine, TX) to properly package, mark, label, and prepare a shipping paper for the item, which was then forwarded to destination.
column169: Informed Customer of need to better train employees on recognizing hazmats, proper shipping requirements, and the serious consequesnces of non-compliance.

column168: On 12/13/2007 at 1030 hrs personnel in the CSXT Queensgate Yard OKC110 discovered FURX 316038, a loaded gondola car (tarp covered) of UN 3262, Sodium Metasilicate, with residue found on the outside of the car from loading on the B-side and BR-side. The car was isolated and Dow Corning was notified. Dow Corning dispatched a team the following morning to address issues and decontaminate car and make ready for further shipping.  Contractor personnel scraped residue and decontaminated the car with neutralizing solution and rearranged tarps for shipment.  At no time was product found to have left the car and fall to the ground. The residue was removed and secured by Dow Corning personnel and the car was released for transportation. This incident did require a special switching move to allow safe access to the car to allow for Dow Corning personnel to perform functions.  Cause Code:  662  NARRI:  5(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100

column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: On 12/5/07 train crew reported north end car in track 17 appeared to be leaking from the top of the car. I looked at the car and found that the car had a minor leak on the air inlet valve at the flange. I placed a receptacle below the leak and informed the yard office that track 17 would be shut down until further notice. I contacted Chemtrec and reported the incident and they informed ExxonMobil of thesituation and they contacted me to let me know they had contacted SWS First Response Co. SWS arrived at aproximately 2300. They discovered product on the top unloading plate under the liquid and air flanges. The liqud air flange was unbolted and raised enough to dry underneath the flange to vizualize its codition.The air flange was then unbolted. the nuts holding the flange wee not sufficently tight. the flange was raised revealing a deformed gasket. The gasket was replaced and bolts were tightened.The spliiage on the outside of the car was wiped down. Job was completed at approximately 0130.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling on Highway 36 just north of Lyons, Texas, vehicle was involved in an accident which punctured the cargo tank.  Approximately 20,000 liquid pounds of free product were released.  The Somerville Fire Department responded to assess the site, along with the Texas Highway Patrol, and Texas Commission on Environmental Quality.  R&D Environmental Services of Channelview, Texas was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  R&D Environmental Services applied absorbent material and saw dust to the affected roadway, and scraped the minimal soil along the road shoulder.  R&D Environmental Services proceeded to use a vacuum truck to recover the free product and water from the affected creek.  Eleven (11) 55-gallon drums of spent absorbent material, sawdust, and soil were transported to R&D Environmental Services’ facility pending disposal.  Approximately 250,000 gallons of contaminated water were pumped from the affected creek.  Analytical samples were taken and submitted to the lab to confirm all levels of contamination had been removed.  There were no injuries or exposures reported as a result of the release.
column169: Since the release was due to a vehicle accident, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Safeway Transportation will continue to reinforce driver safety to all personnel.

column168: On December 23, 2007 at 1332 hours, the CSXT Louisville Division Chief Dispatcher reported train Q51623 was stopped due to a tarp on railcar FURX 315310 that was observed flapping. Further investigation revealed FURX 315310 was leaking rain water that soaked through the tarp. The car was isolated and the Piqua, OH Fire and Police Departments were notified. The Shipper, Dow Corning, was notifed via Chemtrec (report number 2007-1223-00020). CSXT dispatched a response contractor, Veolia Environmental Services, Inc., and personnel  reported liquid was found leaking through drain holes on the gondola car. Veolia personnel plugged the holes and the leak ceased. The car was transported to Lima, OH, where Veolia personnel fitted FURX 315310 with a replacement tarp on December 28, 2007. Veolia personnel advised the original tarp was tied down with poly rope and was loose at the "B" end and every other eyelet was torn and rendered ineffective.    Cause Code:662 (Tarp/Cover Loose)  NARRI:  2 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 40

A BNSF inbound train inspection revealed an entrained 20 foot tank container (JBKU 311032) riding atop an intermodal flatcar emanating a vapor release noise and had ice build-up around the valve/piping area. JBKU 311032 is designated as an AAR U621 intermodal tank container. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder reported the leak source as a cracked liquid line pipe/tubing near an elbow bend. The responder made temporary repairs to eliminate further product vapor release. The intermodal flatcar with JBKU 311032 was setout of the train and isolated in the railyard awaiting further repairs. A consignee technician applied a new shut-off valve on the liquid line pipe along with new Grip-Seal compression fittings which isolated the compromised pipe. Repairs were completed by 0830 hrs. PST, 12/27/07 and JBKU 311032 was released to proceed to its destination.

column168: A BNSF yard switch crew reported GATX 3917 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) emanating a product odor in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected GATX 3917 finding a small amount of liquid product around the 75 psi pressure relief device (PRD). The responder covered the PRD with plastic and sealed it with duct tape. The spillage was cleaned with a bleach/water solution. GATX 3917 was carefully isolated in the railyard awaiting replacement of the PRD that possibly malfunctioned. After the replacement PRD was received, a GATX technician installed it the morning of 1/08/08 and GATX 3917 was released to proceed to its destination 1/08/08 at 1015 hrs PST. The technician indicated the PRD removed appeared to be 'gummed-up' and it was forwarded to a GATX valve shop for a detailed inspection and failure analysis.  Four BNSF employees that were working nearby GATX 3917 at the start of this incident reported product odor exposure. Employees were taken to a local hospital and no treatment was administered to these four employees; and all of them were released to return to work with no restrictions.

A BNSF train derailed its seven rear railcars on single main track due to wide gage from defective/missing crossties. Included in the derailment was one covered hopper ladened with hazardous material. UNPX 127039 (AAR C712, two compartment cylinder type covered hopper) derailed on its side. Three of the four top circular loading hatch closure lids sprung open and granular product spilled from each opened hatchway. The spillage and the opened hatchways were covered in plastic awaiting product recovery. UNPX 127039 (still on its side) was covered with plastic tarps and secured awaiting coordination of product recovery and transfer. Product recovery and transfer was initiated on 1/15/08. The spilled product was shoveled into DOT approved super sacks. The ground area under the open hatches was displaced in order to facilitate the closure of the three open hatches. The open hatches were closed with the closure lids latching properly. A shipper representative was on hand overseeing the product transfer into super sacks. The filled sacks were staged near the site for future transport to be designated by the shipper.

According to the information obtained the following occurred. While transferring freight on the dock approximately 1 pint of UN3077 material was spilled as a result of a forklift puncture.   The only impacted media was the dock floor.  BAX Global, Inc. personnel used gloves, googles, broom and a dust pan to handle cleanup.  BAX Global, Inc. personnel placed down ¼ of a 40 pound bag of absorbents to contain and cleanup the release.  The affected area was also mopped after cleanup.  Approximately 15 pounds of waste was generated as a result of the incident. All waste generated including the cleanup materials and damaged freight were placed into a 30 gallon salvage drum which will be stored in the OSD pending disposition.  The remaining shipment will be held until Dangerous Goods can inspect.  No injuries or exposures were reported. No evacuations were required and no regulatory reporting agencies were notified of the incident.
column169: Since the release was accidental and appears to have been related to a forklift puncture, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, BAX Global, Inc. will continue to rienforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Driver was making a delivery to residential customer and had chains on his bobtail but had to take them off before he got on to the customer’s inclined asphalt driveway per the customer’s request.   Driveway was patchy, some icy spots and some visible asphalt.   EE backed up, parked, and put down chocks.  Driver brought the hose to the customer's tank. Driver noticed that the hose was starting to tighten.  Driver immediately started to disconnect the hose from the tank but could not disconnect in time. The Bobtail had slid down the driveway and the hose ripped completely where the hose meets the connection to the bobtail.  Driver immediately activated a remote emergency shut down device carried on his person.  This shut down all internal valves contained in the truck.  EE drove the out of commission truck back to the SU for repairs. The hose was repaired and the truck is back out making deliveries.

SUNBELT PROJECT MANAGER LARRY SMALLEY RECEIVED THE INITIAL CALL TO RESPOND AT APPROXIMATELY 8:15 AM AND PROCEEDED TO THE SPILL SITE WITH PERSONNEL AND EQUIPMENT. 8:45AM SUNBELT PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON-SITE AND WERE DIRECTED TO STANDBY UNTIL FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL ESTABLISHED THAT THE AREA WAS SAFE TO ENTER. Jack B Kelley (JBK) unit was stopped at a Rail Road crossing with 4 way flashers on. JBK unit was struck in the rearby another semi operated by Zeeland Farm Services, Zeeland, Ml. There were no leaks at the time of the accident. Ittook several hours to extract the driver of the second vehicle, approximately 6 hours later the JBK cargo tankdeveloped a leak. The cargo could not be transferred due to the second vehicle being imbedded into the rear of theJBK unit. The decision was made by the incident commander that due to the flammable conditions the cargo tankwould be allowed to leak until all liquid was dissipated. The LNG was allowed to dissipate into the atmosphere. Thescene was secured and numerous emergency vehicles from the fire department remained in attendance. The cargotank stopped leaking at approximately 2:00 PM the next day. The incident commander decided to let the cargo tankstabilize throughout the night. At 07:30 the next morning the cargo tank was purged with Nitrogen, Compressed gas.The JBK and Zeeland units were separated shortly there after and removed from the scene. The cargo tank wastowed to Alloy Custom products in Delphi, In for evaluation.We have received the following written report from AlloyCustom Products describing the cargo tank failure. We have completed the investigation of damages to Unit E073( Serial Number V3632 ) and the damages as a result of the accident that occurred on US 31 nearPlymouthlN. Wehave determined that the liquid natural gas leaked from a crack in the inner vessel shell that was a result of thecollision. The impact force that was imparted upon the rear of the trailer buckled the jacket and caused the reartandem sub frame to translocate forward and upward at the front of the sub frame.
column169: In our opinion and that of the cargo tank manufacturer, the cargo tank held up extremely well under thecircumstances. The cargo tank sustained a massive blow to the rear of the trailer caused by another semi striking therear at approximately 60 MPH. FMCSA regulations require vehicles transporting hazardous materials to stop atrailroad crossings. In this case there is not a pull out area for the vehicle to stop and the stop must be done in theroadway. Our opinion is that rail road crossings should be exempt if they are protected by crossing gates and/orlights.

Package was inbound from London to Washington. Shipment was loaded on an air cargo pallet and being unloaded in the cargo facility for Worldwide Flight Services at IAD. Shipment was one of two shipments on the air pallet - I PC was IO67kilos, the other was 1PC/1KILO. The first shipment to be removed from the pallet was the one piece at 1 O67kilos. The item was large and bulky and the forklift operator did not see the other shipment as it was pulled under the shipment that was being unloaded. The driver proceeded to drive over to the dangerous goods area (as both shipments were DG) and unknowingly dragged the box all the way to the haz mat area. The item was not able to be located by the warehouse staff and when a search was initiated for the missing box, it was located in the haz mat area. The consignment was found in a damaged state and the area was immediately evacuated until the contents could be verified. The box was damaged/crushed, however, there was no visible spillage. The DG declaration was located which stated what the item was inside the box. The Emergency Response book was immediately checked for clarification on handling the incident. The incident was reported to the local emergency response team and they were dispatched. The incident team arrived on the scene and was given all of the necessary paperwork for their evaluation. The responders determined the item to be of low to moderate hazard as per the ERG and stated that we needed to give the item an over pack. It was agreed and supervised by Fireman Harris to use a secure 5 gallon pail with locking lid. The item was placed in the pail and secured. New DG Class 9 labels were placed on the outside of the bucket and paperwork was attached as well. Item was re secured in the DG area of the warehouse and the response team left. Response team was here approximately 42mm. in total.
column169: Improper forklift procedures lead to this incident. The driver will need to be retrained on proper procedures as well asULD build and break procedures.

column168: UPRR Manager of Yard Operations, reported Tankcars ACFX 86869 and ACFX 79300 were leaking small amounts of product from the top of the car at UPRR Alfalfa Yard El Paso, Texas. Mr. John Jackson, Mgr. Hazardous Materials, was notified and responded. Mr. Jackson discovered the ACFX 79300 had six of eight manway bolts loose, the ACFX 86869 had five of eight manway bolts loose and the manway gaskets deterioratedon both cars. Mr. Jackson notified Viva Environmental to respond and clean the product from the car. The shipper was notified via Chemtrec and responded with two new gaskets. The manway gaskets were replaced, cover closed and all cover bolts tightened properly. Viva personnel cleaned the product form the cars and Mr. Jackson released the cars to destination after reinspection with no other exceptions found.
column169: Shipper will do internal investigation to determine cause of failure.    NARRI: 5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60        Code(s): 200, 209

column168: Driver was headed southbound on Interstate 17 about 30 miles south of Flagstaff, AZ when for unknown reason the truck went off the road and ran into a rock wall. Truck did not impact head on at first but rubbed against wall tearing off side of trailer before full impact occured. at impact trailer broke open and drums were scattered in all directions. The impact and stress caused several drums to rupture and others were crushed underneithe the debris. Impact crushed driver into steering wheel killing him. Driver was in a 75 MPH zone and hit the wall at approximately 76 MPH. He had just come off of home time, left Albuquerque, NM the evening before and was within his legal hours of service. Driver hit wall at approximately 0338. DPS arrived on-scene at approximately 4 am and Rinchem was notified at approximately 0545.     Incident and Spill Commander Polly Wagner arrived on scene at approximately 0930. She called in an outside vendor ERI for Hazmat cleanup. Containment barriers were immediately set up and plan formulated and approved by state officials. Cleanup consisted of pumping off all liquids remaining in drums and any that could be extracted from the soil. Trailer and debris was removed. Rock wall was pressure washed and contaminated soil was removed for remediation. Back fill soil was brought in and landscape restored as much as possible. Cleanup was approved by state officials after work was completed.
column169: Accident investigation and reconstruction is still underway as to the cause of the accident. We are already breifing our drivers on the accident and providing further training on road hazards, fatigue, speed and space management. This accident is in our Corrective Action Process and as more is learned we will implement measures to reduce the risk of this happening again.

Geo dynamic’s driver arrived at the Generator’s facility to pick up a load of waste sulfuric/nitric acid at approximately 2:30 PM on December 14, 2007. After the waste acid was loaded in the truck, the driver was instructed by a Mold Tech [Generator] employee to clean the acid solution from the inside of his loading hoses by vacuuming water from an adjacent tank, through the hoses into the cargo tank, where the water mixed with the concentrated acid. GEodynamic believes that such a mixture resulted in a highly exothermic reaction, and under such temperatures and conditions, the reacting acid solution attacked even the acid resistant surfaces of the interior of the cargo tank, and the corrosion-resistant valve assembly used to fill and empty the tank. It seems apparent from the post incident condition of the valve assembly, that such acid attack of the metal occurred, resulting in a leak. Geodynamic’s truck left the Mold Tech facility at about 3:15 PM; at that time, although the reaction was presumably taking place inside the tank, there were no outwardly visible signs. The truck had only proceeded approximately a mile from the facility when leakage was observed from the valve assembly at the rear of the truck. Geodynamic’s driver moved the truck to the closest available area isolated from residential areas or nearby structures, and called emergency services (911), which responded promptly. As a safety precaution, employees at two nearby businesses (Champion Steel and Cadence Innovation) were sent home early that day.

The shipment was offered under a vessel sharing agreement to Hapag-Lloyd Container Line by Atlantic Container Line (ACL), on behalf of their shipper,for transport on the Hapag-Lloyd container vessel Leverkusen Express from Savannah, Georgia to Antwerp, Belgium.The shipment was declared for only one item of hazardous material - UN3269, Polyester Resin Kit, Class 3, PG III.ACL advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel had sailed from Savannah that in addition to the item originally booked - UN1866, Resin Solution, Class 3, PGIII was also loaded in the freight container.The shipping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not reflect the additional hazardous material.ACL subsequentially provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd and the Master was advised of the additional item.

The aircraft was loaded in Sheldon Point, AK (SXP) with approximately 33 bottles of carbon dioxide. In order to fit the rack in the aircraft with the 12 bottles in it, the Captain removed the safety caps from the six outside bottles. They flew to Aniak(ANI)for fuel. The approximate taxi time out of ANI was 1835 after fueling 180 gallons of Jet A and loading 92 Ibs of mail and freight. The destination was Anchorage, AK. On departure the crew heard hissing from a bottle and aborted the Takeoff. They taxied back to the ramp and lost consciousness during shutdown. The parking brake was set. The condition levers were in fuel cutoff and the props feathered. Everything else was left on. The crew had picked up an IFR clearance from Anchorage Center. Anchorage Center call Steve Hill of Inland Aviation who is the Agent for Alaska Central Express and told him they had not activated there flight plan. He proceeded out to the ramp and discovered the crew in the aircraft. He then removed them from the aircraft and went in to the office to call 911. The crew regained consciousness and was transported to the Aniak Clinic and were subsequently medivaced to Anchorage. They were released approximately 9 hours after the incident, the Cylinders were marked 50 Lbs and placarded Non Flammable Gas.
column169: If the crew had followed Company Procedures and FAA regulations this would not have happened.

column43: LITHIUM MANGANESE BATTERY CONTAINED IN SSCOR BRAND HAN
column168: The package contained a handheld, battery-operated medical suction pump, containing a lithium manganese battery. It was unloaded from the trailer at 00:10. It was sorted on to the transverse conveyor at 00:27 where it spontaneously combusted. An employee in the area was able to extinguish the fire using a facility fire extinguisher. The maintenance mechanics arrived on scene and doused the surrounding area with water from a pressurized water fire extinguisher. There were no other packages in the vicinity and there was no damage to the conveyor belt or any other equipment. Even though this shipment appears excepted from the Hazardous Material Regulations, company management advised completing this DOT 5800.1 report due to the package containing Lithium Manganese batteries.
column169: Recommend expert evaluation of battery and device to determine cause of fire.

column168: As the roll off box was being loaded onto a trailer material leaked out through the back of the box. The material that was loaded into the roll off box was a solid but at the time of pick up there was ice on top and apparently liquid at the bottom of the box. When the box was set off onto the lot no material or water leaked out. It was not until after the temperatures had risen above freezing that the ice melted causing there to be free liquids in the roll off box. Once the operator noticed that the box was leaking, the box was placed on the ground. The Transportation Safety Assistant was contacted and was sent to evaluate the scene. Once there, the TSA placed absorbent material around the affected area and roped it off to ensure no other vehicles would travel through the area and that no material would get into any sewers, stormwater systems, or soil.
column169: The generator has been made aware of this situation and will take measures to ensure that all free liquids have been pumped out prior to Heritage Transport picking up the roll off box.

column168: Chris Hopkins, Train Dispatcher WSO5O1O, advised via Avtec the crew of westbound Train QEWWC 06, Lead Locomotive UP 5477, reported an eastbound train advised of a propane odor as they passed the westbound train at Mile Post 654,4 of the Yuma Subdivision. Robert Bavier, Manager Hazardous Materials, and Duffy Exxon, Manager Field Operations, were notified. At 04:32 AM, Chris Hopkins, Train Dispatcher WSO5O1O, advised the area of the smell was located around tankcar NATX 72630. At 05:10 AM. Manager Bavier responded. Thomas Farrell, Senior Special Agent Hazmat also responded. At 07:08 AM, Kevin, Niland Fire Department, reported that the inspection had been stopped after a sheriff’s deputy was taken to the hospital after feeling sick from walking near the train. At 07:33 AM, Bavier reported that tank car NATX 72630 had released vapor only from a loose manway and bad gasket. Repairs were made and the train was released to transportation. At 9:24AM, the Imperial County Sheriff’s Department reported that the deputy had been released from the hospital after receiving breathing treatments for an inhalation injury. The following day, claim representative advised that the brakeman of the east bound train been treated for exposure to the fumes and eye Irritation.

column168: Our company tractor and trailer were traveling westbound on FM 652. Upon approaching a sharp curve on the roadway. Tractor and trailer failed to negotiate the curve and traveled across the roadway diagonally through the leftlane. Tractor and trailer rolled on the roadway to the north striking two road signs and continued off the roadway through a fence. Tractor and trailer came to rest approximately 40 feet off the roadway in a pasture. Tractor came to rest upside down on top of trailer which came to rest on its side. Driver of the tractor was trapped under cab of tractor.     No hazardous material was released. Accident was reported to Railroad Commission of Texas. Cargo tank was sent for repair and recertificatfon. 94 Photographs attached.

column168: Theresa Santistevan, Car Foreman Supervisor, reported a propane hke odor emitted from the receiving yard near track 205 and 206 inside the West Colton Yard in Colton, CA. Robert Bavier, Manager Hazardous Materials, was notified and responded. At 12:13 PM, Bavieradvised tankcar involved was GATX 58046. Mr. Bavier stated the vapor was released as a result of loose manway bolts. Mr. Bavier advised the bolts were tightened, repairs were completed, and the tankcar was released. ;1

Dean Cooper, Manager, Hazardous Materials, reported one or more drums in container CRXU 300554 was releasing product onto the pavement in Stall White 166, ICTF, Long Beach, CA. Mr. Cooper stated there was minimal product on the ground and there were no waterways affected. Transloading Environmental, Contractor, was contracted to respond. Los Angeles City Fire Department personnel had arrived at the yard and requested entry. At 04:42PM, Manager Cooper reported remediation was in progress and would not be complete for another three hours. While unloading the drums, located four drums that had micro stress cracks on the lower head of the reconditioned drums, which released product. The four leaking drums were patched and placed into salvage drums for securement. After cleaning the residue inside the container, the undamaged drums along with the salvage drums, were placed back into the original container for over the road movement onto the consignee, per the shippers instructions.

column168: A transport company driver delivering sulfuric acid to a Calpine facility was sprayed with 93% sulfuric acid following the rupture of the driver’s hose as he initiated a transfer. The driver was wearing a face shield but not mono-goggles. Liquid from the ruptured hose caused the drivers hard hat and face shield to come off resulting in bums to the drivers face and eyes.      DRIVER HAD 2 STOPS INSIDE THE PLANT.  HE UNLOADED APX 900 GALLONS AT 1ST STOP HE KEPT PRESSURE ON TANK AND WENT TO 2ND STOP.  HE USED A NON COMPANY NOT AUTHORIZED HOSE & FAILED TO WAIT FOR UNLOADER TO OPEN VALVES.  PRESSURE IN THE TANK & CLOSED VALVE ON CUSTOMERS TANK CAUSED HOSE TO RUPTURE & SPRAY DRIVER.  DRIVER IS A CONTRACTOR & NOT AN EMPLOYEE.  COMPANY PROVIDES TRAILER ONLY.
column169: Delivery drivers should review their unloading procedures with the Calpine employee supervising the unloading to ensure both parties have an awareness of unloading process. Typical unloading procedures from sulfuric manufacturers recommend that the delivery truck’s cargo vessel have pressure gradually applied to the delivery tank after establishing flow through the transfer system. If the driver’s procedure is not consistent with this, additional measures should be taken which contemplate a high velocity release.  Pre-transfer inspections of transfer hoses should include focus on potential stress points such as (onnections which cause the hose to make a 90 degree angle turn Hose connections having 45 degree angle fittings directed downward and physical support will reduce stress on the hose under the weight of the product and reduce the failure potential during liquid transfer.  All personnel should wear mono-goggles while in the immediate area during chemical transfers.      AWARNESS TO ALL DRIVERS TO INSPECT HOSES & FOLLOW PROCEEDURES WHEN UNLOADING

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. column168: It was snowing and a very wet snow. Driver pulled in to unload gasoline at a gas station. The parking area to make the delivery is on a slight grade and the parking lot had .not yet been plowed or sanded. The driver secured the unit and started making the delivery. As the equipment got lighter from unloading, ice had formed under the hot tires and the unit started slidding away. Driver paniced and went to the truck instead of shutting down the flow of gasoline into the storage tank. The tractor tires ran over the unloading hose and stopped at that point, but the hose was pulled off of the trailer and started spilling. The driver shut the valve off as soon as he could spilling about 50 gallons of gasoline. The driver immediatly placed absorbant pads down at the sewer manhole, called 911 and the Vadnais Heights, MN fire department HazMat team was sent to the location. They placed aborbant pads down and floor dry as well as diked the area at the culverts from the storm sewer system. West Central Environmental Consultants, Moms, MN was contracted to clean up and discard the remaining product and finish the clean-up and dispose of all hazardous materials involved in .the clean up. The Minnesota Pollution Control was also notified and they were also at the scene for an assesment of the spill. MN Duty report number 93451.
column169: We will not be delivering fuel to this location when the parking area is slippery and not sanded. Whenever it is snowing or an ice storm, we will not make a delivery to this station to avoid a reaccurance of this type of spill.

column168: 12/21/2007   Sacramento Airport - While Ramp agent was unloading Southwest flight 659 from SWAt0 SMF, he noticed a smell of formalin solution coming from one package in a shipment of 3. The agent notices a small amount, approximately 10 ounces of fluid on the cargo bin. The box was removed and isolated to prevent further contamination. The package was opened to verify what was leaking. There were three internal packages and one was leaking and seemed to be formalin solution. Pictures were taken of the external packaging as well as all internal items and packaging. Ramp Supervisor and Southwest Maintenance was notified and cargo bin was disinfected. Southwest Safety Department was also notified. Safety Department made sure all steps were taken and then notified Robert Cassidy with the   FAA’s Western Region office.

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. IF ATTACHMENTS USED FOR FORKLIFT ARE IMPROPERLY WORKING, THEY MUST BE REMOVED FROM SERVICE AND BE REPAIRED OR TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE PERMANENTLY. MAINTENANCE MUST BE DONE PROPERLY TO ENSURE SAFETY USE FOR ALL. WHEN ENTERING OR EXITING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS, OR TOTES LOADED OR STACKED ON THE FLOOR; ON A PLATFORM AND OR HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASYPUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING. LEAVE PAIL OF HAZARDOUS OR CHEMICAL IN THE BAY UNTIL TRAILER IS READY FOR CLOSE. EMPLOYEEGIVEN COACHING ON LOADING AND DOCK AWARENESS.

column168: OUR TRUCK WAS TRAVELING NORHT BOUND ON INDUSTRIAL ROAD AT APPOX. 40 MPH.  AS WE APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION OF OLD MOBILE HWY, A CAR WHICH HAD BEEN TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON OLD MOBILE HWY FAILED TO STOP AT THE SIGN AND MADE A LEFT TURN ON TO INDUSTRIAL ROAD IN FRON OF OUR TRUCK.  OUR DRIVER HAD TO BRAKE HARD TO TRY TO AVOID STRIKING THIS CAR IN THE REAR.  WE ALSO HAD TO STEER THE TRUCK TOWARDS THE DIRT SHOULDER TO AVOID CAR.  OUR DRIVER MISSED THE CAR AND CAME TO A STOP WITH THE RIGHT (PASSENGER) TIRES ON SHOULDER AND THE LEFT (DRIVER SIDE) TIRES ON ROADWAY.  THERE WAS AN APPROX 8" TO 10" DROP  OFF FROM PAVEMENT TO DIRT SHOULD WHERE HE CAME TO A STOP.  THIS DROP OFF IS NOT READILY VISIBLE DUE TO TALL GRASS & WOODS GROWING ON SHOULDER. ALSO DIRT AT THIS SPOT WAS SOFT DUE TO RECENT RAINS.  ONCE TRUCK WAS AT A FULL STOP, IT PROCEEDED TO DO A SOFT ROLL OVER ONTO IT'S RIGHT SIDE DUE TO THIS SIDEWAYS ANGLE. MINOR LEAKAGE FROM THE TANKERS TOP GASKET DUE TO ROLL OVER.

Driver was traveling northbound behind school bus in left lane of two lanes per direcci After passing through the intersection of Grace Street and Lancaster Ave the school bus which was traveling between lanes, stopped suddenly. Driver applied brakes and started to skid. Driver then steered right to avoid hitting school bus. The truck then starte I to skid sideways. The truck then overturned onto driver’s side damaging the tank, Fuel then leaked from the tank (approx 1500 gallons).   Of the 1500 total, 490 gallons was pumped off the street leaving approximately. 1000 gallons entering the stormwater pipe system. Several hundred gallons were recovered from vaults and storm sewers along the pipe system. Harbor boom captured oil at the outfall of the stormwater sewer as it entered the water. The FADE? estimated that approx 200 gallons entered the River.

column168: Driver noticed a puff of smoke out of his trailer while headed north on I-5. He pulled over into the Gee Creek Rest Area around mile marker 11. The trailer had sprung a pinhole leak above the driver's side fender. He called Dispatch and we alerted the Zurich NA Spill Center and local 911 ER. Driver tried to plug the leak and it grew a little larger. We dispatched a clean lined trailer to the scene to transfer the load and stop the leak. We took an air activated diaphragm pump to the site. We transferred the product and stopped the leak at @ 07:25. Our response team from NRC Environmental covered the area with acid neutralizer. The state patrol released the driver and trailer to return to the yard and released the other trailer to deliver the load. NRC Environmental added soda ash to the collection pond & parking lot to neutralize. Neutralized wash-down water was collected and removed for disposal. We calculate @ 200-215 gallons was spilled.
column169: We are discussing a change in the annual lining test interval. We have purchased conductivity meters to check conductivity of product to the steel barrel. We are in the process of negotiating with shippers to make conductivity testing as part of their loading procedure.

column168: OUR TRUCK WAS TRAVELING NORTH BOUND ON INDUSTRIAL ROAD AT APPROX. 40 MPH. AS HE APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION OF OLD MOBILE  HWY. A CAR WHICH HAD BEEN TRAVELING EAST BOUND ON OLD MOBILE HWY FAILED TO STOP AT THE STOP SIGN AND MADE A LEFT TURN ONTO INDUSTRIAL ROAD IN FRONT OF OUR TRUCK. OUR DRIVER HAD TO BRAKE HARD TO TRY TO AVOID STRIKING THIS CAR IN THE REAR. HE ALSO HAD TO STEER THE TRUCK TOWARDS THE DIRT SHOULDER TO AVOID CAR. OUR DRIVER MISSED THE CAR AND CAME TO A STOP WITH THE RIGHT (PRECISION) TIRES ON SHOULDER AND THE LEFT (DRIVER SIDE) TIRES ON ROADWAY. THERE WAS AN APPROX 8" TO 10" DROP OFF FROM PAVEMENT TO DIRT SHOULDER WHERE HE CAME TO A STOP. THIS DROP OFF IS NOT READILY VISIBLE DUE TO TALL GRASS & WOODS GROWING ON SHOULDER. ALSO DIRT AT THE SPOT WAS SOFT DUE TO RECENT RAINS. ONLY TRUCK WAS AT A FULL STOP. IT PROCEEDED TO DO A SOFT ROLL OVER ONTO IT'S RIGHT SIDE DUE TO THIS SIDEWAYS ANGLE. MINOR LEAKAGE FROM THE TANKERS TOP GASKET DUE TO ROLL OVER.
column169: AS THERE IS A SLIGHT CURVE IN ROADWAY ON INDUSTRIAL ROAD TO THE SOUTH OF THIS INTERSECTION AND AS THIS IS THE MAIN ROAD INTO THE CHEVRON REFINERY AND OTHER CHEMICAL PLANTS-THERE POSSIBLY SHOULD BE A TRAFFIC LIGHT AT THIS INTERSECTION.

UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE AND EMITTING A GASOLINE ODOR. THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN A LAWNMOWER ENGINE WITH GAS STILL INSIDE OF THE TANK. THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT DECLARED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.   CLEAR OF SCENE: 1030.   THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.
